Yes it's true. You must use (for this recipe at least) regular supermarket chili powder, not the pure stuff made only from chilies. Be aware; like the previous reviewer stated, if you add pure chipotle or ancho, it will be much too spicy. Bon Appetit should better clarify things next time.

Rating: 3
Rather an ordinary chili, apart from the chipotles and the black beans. I couldn't purchase the chipotles so I used the regular green and red chilies which were also very good. To compensate for the absence of smoky taste I started with frying some bacon and added the crispy bits as an accompaniment. The black beans were somewhat spicier than the usual red beans. A nice change.

Rating: 2
I made a mistake and took the advice of another reviewer and used Ancho chile powder and Chipotle chile powder in equal amounts in addition to the canned chipotle chiles in Adobo and the chili wound up being FIRE ENGINE HOT!!!! I could barely eat it! I was so disappointed, but I didn't realize the chipotle powder was going to be so hot. I immediately called my sister in NM and asked her how do I fix it and she said add sugar and some water and serve with plenty of fritos or tortilla chips. It was still very hot but tasty. Next time I'll know better! Otherwise, I followed the recipe as stated. BTW, the crema was terrific, don't leave it out!

