Made this for a Saint Patty's party (to use some of the stout. It was too hot for many of our neighbor's (mid-west buds!), but for the heat lover's it was great. The lime crema is a nice touch and a great flavor combo with the smokey chipotle's. It won't replace my standard chili recipe (not tomatoey enough)but a good new addition. Also a great slow-cooker recipe - brown the beef and then the onions as indicated, then add the rest to the crock pot and let it simmer!

Rating: 3
Absolutely wonderful! I subbed stew meat for the ground, as I prefer the texture in chili, and eyeballed most of the measurements (onions, chipotles), but I'm fairly accurate with that. This is wonderfully flavorful, with a lingering heat. The lime crema is very good, but my husband and daughter preferred it with crumbled queso fresco. Definitely will be repeated. (Might be good with pork chunks also)

Rating: 3
Easy and excellent. For the previous reviewers - you have to use REAL chili powder, not something like a Schilling brand which is mostly salt, garlic etc and very little chili powder. Go to a Mexican market (or order online)or check this Hispanic food section of your grocery. We used a combination of Ancho, New Mexico and California chili powders - used half black beans and half kidney beans. Used 1/2 ground pork and 1/2 ground beef (extra lean)and threw in a Tbsp of cumin. And it's the Chipotle chilies that are not, not the chili powders! Found this to a rich and delicious chili recipe.

